	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>rainwarrior</b> [ Sun Feb 26, 2017 9:36 am ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: Can we still get a collection of NSF without sound effec</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />I appreciate NSFs having sound effects if possible, and I thought NSFe had a potentially good solution to the problem by adopting a convention:<br /><br />Put all the music tracks in the NSFe playlist, and leave all the sound effects out of it. That way sound effects can be played by turning off the playlist and just listening to all tracks.<br /><br />I think this is suitable because I don't imagine anyone really wants to listen to a &quot;playlist&quot; of sound effects. You're probably either trying to find a specific one to record or something, or just want to listen to them all to investigate what's in there, which also doesn't need a playlist.<br /><br />Of course, we could just add an additional NSFe chunk that identifies which tracks are SFX, and then it could just be a &quot;sound effects&quot; option in the player.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


